#Text=VII
#Text=ON Saturday night Dr. Archie went with Fred Ottenburg to hear “ Tannhauser . ”

#Text=Thea had a rehearsal on Sunday afternoon , but as she was not on the bill again until Wednesday , she promised to dine with Archie and Ottenburg on Monday , if they could make the dinner early .
#Text=At a little after eight on Monday evening , the three friends returned to Thea 's apartment and seated themselves for an hour of quiet talk .
#Text=“ I 'm sorry we could n't have had Landry with us tonight , ” Thea said , “ but he 's on at Weber and Fields ' every night now .
#Text=You ought to hear him , Dr. Archie .
#Text=He often sings the old Scotch airs you used to love . ”
#Text=“ Why not go down this evening ? ” Fred suggested hopefully , glancing at his watch .
#Text=“ That is , if you 'd like to go .
#Text=I can telephone and find what time he comes on . ”
#Text=Thea hesitated .
#Text=“ No , I think not .
#Text=I took a long walk this afternoon and I 'm rather tired .
#Text=I think I can get to sleep early and be so much ahead .
#Text=I do n't mean at once , however , ” seeing Dr. Archie 's disappointed look .
#Text=“ I always like to hear Landry , ” she added .
#Text=“ He never had much voice , and it 's worn , but there 's a sweetness about it , and he sings with such taste . ”
#Text=“ Yes , does n't he ?
#Text=May I ? ”
#Text=Fred took out his cigarette case .
#Text=“ It really does n't bother your throat ? ”
#Text=“ A little does n't .
#Text=But cigar smoke does .
#Text=Poor Dr. Archie !
#Text=Can you do with one of those ? ”
#Text=“ I 'm learning to like them , ” the doctor declared , taking one from the case Fred proffered him .
#Text=“ Landry 's the only fellow I know in this country who can do that sort of thing , ” Fred went on .
#Text=“ Like the best English ballad singers .
#Text=He can sing even popular stuff by higher lights , as it were . ”
#Text=Thea nodded .
#Text=“ Yes ; sometimes I make him sing his most foolish things for me .
#Text=It 's restful , as he does it .
#Text=That 's when I 'm homesick , Dr. Archie . ”
#Text=“ You knew him in Germany , Thea ? ”
#Text=Dr. Archie had quietly abandoned his cigarette as a comfortless article .
#Text=“ When you first went over ? ”
#Text=“ Yes .
#Text=He was a good friend to a green girl .
#Text=He helped me with my German and my music and my general discouragement .
#Text=Seemed to care more about my getting on than about himself .
#Text=He had no money , either .
#Text=An old aunt had loaned him a little to study on .
#Text=-- Will you answer that , Fred ? ”
#Text=Fred caught up the telephone and stopped the buzz while Thea went on talking to Dr. Archie about Landry .
#Text=Telling some one to hold the wire , he presently put down the instrument and approached Thea with a startled expression on his face .
#Text=“ It 's the management , ” he said quietly .
#Text=“ Gloeckler has broken down : fainting fits .
#Text=Madame Rheinecker is in Atlantic City and Schramm is singing in Philadelphia tonight .
#Text=They want to know whether you can come down and finish SIEGLINDE . ”
#Text=“ What time is it ? ”
#Text=“ Eight fifty-five .
#Text=The first act is just over .
#Text=They can hold the curtain twenty-five minutes . ”
#Text=Thea did not move .
#Text=“ Twenty-five and thirty-five makes sixty , ” she muttered .
#Text=“ Tell them I 'll come if they hold the curtain till I am in the dressing-room .
#Text=Say I 'll have to wear her costumes , and the dresser must have everything ready .
#Text=Then call a taxi , please . ”
#Text=Thea had not changed her position since he first interrupted her , but she had grown pale and was opening and shutting her hands rapidly .
#Text=She looked , Fred thought , terrified .
#Text=He half turned toward the telephone , but hung on one foot .
#Text=“ Have you ever sung the part ? ” he asked .
#Text=“ No , but I 've rehearsed it .
#Text=That 's all right .
#Text=Get the cab . ”
#Text=Still she made no move .
#Text=She merely turned perfectly blank eyes to Dr. Archie and said absently , “ It 's curious , but just at this minute I ca n't remember a bar of ' Walkure ' after the first act .
#Text=And I let my maid go out . ”
#Text=She sprang up and beckoned Archie without so much , he felt sure , as knowing who he was .
#Text=“ Come with me . ”
#Text=She went quickly into her sleeping-chamber and threw open a door into a trunk-room .
#Text=“ See that white trunk ?
#Text=It 's not locked .
#Text=It 's full of wigs , in boxes .
#Text=Look until you find one marked ' Ring 2 . '
#Text=Bring it quick ! ”
#Text=While she directed him , she threw open a square trunk and began tossing out shoes of every shape and color .
#Text=Ottenburg appeared at the door .
#Text=“ Can I help you ? ”
#Text=She threw him some white sandals with long laces and silk stockings pinned to them .
#Text=“ Put those in something , and then go to the piano and give me a few measures in there -- you know . ”

#Text=She was behaving somewhat like a cyclone now , and while she wrenched open drawers and closet doors , Ottenburg got to the piano as quickly as possible and began to herald the reappearance of the Volsung pair , trusting to memory .
#Text=In a few moments Thea came out enveloped in her long fur coat with a scarf over her head and knitted woolen gloves on her hands .
#Text=Her glassy eye took in the fact that Fred was playing from memory , and even in her distracted state , a faint smile flickered over her colorless lips .
#Text=She stretched out a woolly hand , “ The score , please .
#Text=Behind you , there . ”
#Text=Dr. Archie followed with a canvas box and a satchel .
#Text=As they went through the hall , the men caught up their hats and coats .
#Text=They left the music-room , Fred noticed , just seven minutes after he got the telephone message .
#Text=In the elevator Thea said in that husky whisper which had so perplexed Dr. Archie when he first heard it , “ Tell the driver he must do it in twenty minutes , less if he can .
#Text=He must leave the light on in the cab .
#Text=I can do a good deal in twenty minutes .
#Text=If only you had n't made me eat --
#Text=Damn that duck ! ” she broke out bitterly ; “ why did you ? ”
